---
Type Organization:
- Place shared types in src/types
- Group by domain/feature
- Use index files for exports
- Follow naming conventions
- Document complex types

Prisma Types:
- Extend Prisma types for full models
- Create partial types for forms
- Define proper relations
- Use type helpers (Pick, Omit)
- Example: type FullUser = User & { profile: Profile }

Component Types:
- Define prop interfaces
- Use HTMLProps when extending HTML elements
- Type event handlers properly
- Handle optional props
- Example: interface ButtonProps extends React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>

Schema Types:
- Use Zod for runtime validation
- Define schema types in src/schemas
- Generate TypeScript types from schemas
- Keep schemas and types in sync
- Example: const UserSchema = z.object({...})

Best Practices:
- Prefer interfaces over types
- Use strict type checking
- Avoid any and unknown
- Implement proper generics
- Use satisfies operator for type validation

Common Patterns:
- ActionResult<T> for server actions
- ComponentProps<T> for components
- RouteParams for dynamic routes
- RequestBody for API endpoints
- ResponseData for API responses